(1) a-diversity metrics comparison

#Format data 
format_adiv <- function(adiv_df, metadata_df, metric_col) {
  rownames(adiv_df) <- adiv_df$SampleID
  df <- metadata_df[rownames(adiv_df), , drop = FALSE]
  df[[metric_col]] <- adiv_df[[metric_col]]
  df}

# (1) global comparison (KW and Dunn's post hoc test) 
# objective: determine whether diversity depends on global vaginal microbial composition,
# this analysis was performed using one sample per patient (n = 1,547) rather than 1,957 samples 
# in order to satisfy the assumption of independence of observations.
compute_univ <- function(data, y, group, group_levels, patient_col) {
  
  df <- data[, c(y, group, patient_col), drop = FALSE]
  df <- df[!duplicated(df[[patient_col]]), , drop = FALSE]
  df[[group]] <- factor(df[[group]], levels = group_levels)
  kw <- kruskal.test(as.formula(paste(y, "~", group)), data = df)
  dunn <- dunn.test::dunn.test(x = df[[y]],
                               g = df[[group]],
                               method = "bh",
                               kw = FALSE,
                               list = TRUE)
  list(data = df,
       n_by_group = table(df[[group]]),
       kruskal = kw,
       dunn = dunn)}

# (2) comparison of genes Detection frequency  (Chi-square and pairwise fisher tests)
compute_prop <- function(df_abun, metadata, group, group_levels) {
  samp <- rownames(df_abun)
  df <- metadata[samp, , drop = FALSE]
  df <- df[, group, drop = FALSE]
  df[[group]] <- factor(df[[group]], levels = group_levels)

  detected <- ifelse(rowSums(df_abun > 0, na.rm = TRUE) > 0, 1, 0)
  df$detected <- detected
  df <- df[complete.cases(df), , drop = FALSE]
  tab <- table(df[[group]], df$detected)

  chisq <- chisq.test(tab)
  fisher <- pairwise.fisher.test(x = df$detected, g = df[[group]],p.adjust.method = "BH")
  prop <- prop.table(tab, margin = 1)
  
  list(df = df, 
       table = tab, 
       proportion = prop, 
       chisq = chisq, 
       fisher = fisher)
}

(b) For Pregnancy related clinical outcomes

We fitted a linear mixed-effects models (GLMMs) to investigate associations while adjusting for covariates and accounting for repeated measures (patient ID).

Firstly, we constructed a univariate models, accounting for repeated measures to reflect the overall distribution.

We subsequently built a multivariate models to estimate the independent contribution of each variable

Note Only clinical variables that significantly differed across clinical groups were included in the multivariate models (See supplementary tables).

Variables dictionary: BIL_INC_ATB (Antibiotics): antibiotic exposure during pregnancy PAT_AGE (Age): maternal age IMC (BMI): body mass index CERCLAGE (Cervical cerclage) RCIU (IUGR): intrauterine growth restriction DIABET_GESTA (Gestational diabetes) HTA_PRE_ECLAM (Hypertension / preeclampsia): hypertensive disorders of pregnancy

# Given that ARG and MGE diversity metrics are zero-inflated and 
# that zero values represent biologically meaningful information, these metrics will be analyzed using hurdle models (binomial + Gaussian).
# This approach allows a biologically coherent analysis of presence/absence, followed by composition when present
# Species diversity metrics will be analyzed using a Gaussian model (Log transformed) (see model performance)

### GLMMs models construction

#Gaussian model 
run_glmm_gauss <- function(adiv_df, metadata_df, response, family, 
                           fixed_effect, covariates = NULL, random_effect,
                           transform, reference) {
  names(adiv_df)[1] <- "SampleID"
  adiv_df$SampleID <- as.character(adiv_df$SampleID)
  metadata_df$SampleID <- as.character(metadata_df$SampleID)

  keep_meta <- c("SampleID", fixed_effect, covariates, random_effect)
  keep_meta <- keep_meta[!is.na(keep_meta) & keep_meta != ""]
  keep_meta <- unique(keep_meta)

  df <- merge(adiv_df, metadata_df[, keep_meta, drop = FALSE], by = "SampleID")

  df[[fixed_effect]] <- factor(df[[fixed_effect]])
  if (!is.null(reference)) df[[fixed_effect]] <- relevel(df[[fixed_effect]], ref = reference)

  df$resp <- transform(df[[response]])
  df <- df[complete.cases(df[, c("resp", fixed_effect, covariates, random_effect), drop = FALSE]), , drop = FALSE]

  rhs_full <- paste(c(fixed_effect, covariates, paste0("(1|", random_effect, ")")), collapse = " + ")
  mod_full <- glmmTMB(as.formula(paste("resp ~", rhs_full)), data = df, family = family)
  emm <- emmeans(mod_full, fixed_effect)
  pw  <- as.data.frame(pairs(emm, adjust = "tukey"))

  list(df = df, mod_full = mod_full, pairs = pw)}
#hurdle model (binomial + gaussian)
run_glmm_hurdle <- function(adiv_df, metadata_df, response,
                            fixed_effect, covariates = NULL,
                            random_effect, reference, presence_col) {
  # Format data (drop NaN values, as the # of NaN are negligible)
  keep_meta <- c("SampleID", fixed_effect, covariates, random_effect)
  keep_meta <- keep_meta[!is.na(keep_meta) & keep_meta != ""]
  keep_meta <- unique(keep_meta)
  df <- merge(adiv_df, metadata_df[, keep_meta, drop = FALSE], by = "SampleID")

  df[[fixed_effect]] <- factor(df[[fixed_effect]])
  df[[fixed_effect]] <- relevel(df[[fixed_effect]], ref = reference)

  df$y <- df[[response]]
  df <- df[complete.cases(
    df[, c("y", presence_col, fixed_effect, covariates, random_effect),
       drop = FALSE]), , drop = FALSE]

  df$detected <- df[[presence_col]]

  rhs <- paste(c(fixed_effect, covariates, paste0("(1|", random_effect, ")")),
               collapse = " + ")
#model 
  mod_det <- glmmTMB(as.formula(paste("detected ~", rhs)),
                     data = df,family = binomial())
  
  # PART II : conditional (gaussian) ---> + samples 
  df_pos <- df[df[[presence_col]] == 1, , drop = FALSE]
  df_pos$resp <- log1p(df_pos$y)

  mod_cont <- glmmTMB(
    as.formula(paste("resp ~", rhs)),
    data = df_pos,
    family = gaussian()
  )
  
  #  contrasts
  emm_det <- emmeans(mod_det, specs = fixed_effect, type = "response")
  pairs_det <- pairs(emm_det, adjust = "tukey")

  emm_cont <- emmeans(mod_cont, specs = fixed_effect)
  pairs_cont <- pairs(emm_cont, adjust = "tukey")

  list(
    df_all = df,
    df_pos = df_pos,
    mod_detection = mod_det,
    mod_conditional = mod_cont,
    emm_detection = emm_det,
    tukey_detection = pairs_det,
    emm_conditional = emm_cont,
    tukey_conditional = pairs_cont
  )}

# function to evaluate model performance
diag_glmmTMB <- function(mod, name, nsim = 1000, perf = TRUE) {
  cat("Diagnostics:", name, "\n")

  # DHARMa: QQ plot only
  sim <- DHARMa::simulateResiduals(mod, n = nsim)
  DHARMa::plotQQunif(sim)

  # Collinearity (only for multivariate models)
  if (perf) {col <- performance::check_collinearity(mod)
  plot(col)}
}

# Align matrix with metadata ID 
align_meta_mat <- function(mat, meta) {
  s <- intersect(rownames(mat), rownames(meta))
  list(mat = mat[s, , drop = FALSE], meta = meta[s, , drop = FALSE])}

# PERMANOVA using Adonis 
adonis_analysis <- function(matrice, metadata, formula, method, by = NULL, permutations = 999) {
  dist <- vegdist(as.matrix(matrice), method = method)
  adonis2(dist ~ ., data = model.frame(formula, metadata),by = by, permutations = permutations)}

#Plot R2 results for IN and SN 
plot_adonis_R2 <- function(res_IN, res_SN, title = NULL) {
  df_IN <- as.data.frame(res_IN)
  df_SN <- as.data.frame(res_SN)
  terms <- intersect(rownames(df_IN), rownames(df_SN))
  terms <- setdiff(terms, c("Residual", "Total"))
  r2 <- cbind(IN = df_IN[terms, "R2"],SN = df_SN[terms, "R2"])
  
  xmax <- max(r2, na.rm = TRUE) * 1.2
  op <- par(mar = c(4, 8, 4, 4))
  on.exit(par(op))

  barplot(t(r2),horiz = TRUE, beside = TRUE,
          col = c("blue", "grey"),
          xlab = "PERMANOVA R",
          main = title,
          xlim = c(0, xmax),
          names.arg = terms,las = 2,
          legend.text = c("IN", "SN"), 
          args.legend = list(bty = "n", x = "bottomright"))}
# Split metadata by sampling type (inclusion : IN ; Delivery (SN))
metadata_IN <- metadata[metadata$Type == "IN", , drop = FALSE]
metadata_SN <- metadata[metadata$Type == "SN", , drop = FALSE]

metadata_SN <- as.data.frame(metadata_SN)
rownames(metadata_IN) <- metadata_IN$SampleID
rownames(metadata_SN) <- metadata_SN$SampleID

(3) Differential abundance analysis (using MaAslin2)

To evaluate features differential abundance, we applied two different models to account for the structure of the dat:

LM_CLR: CLR-transformed linear model, used for microbial species. CPLM: used for ARGs and MGEs, which are rarer

# Build a function to run MaAsLin2 using the two different models described above and extract a standard output for visualisation. 
maaslin_go <- function(count_data, metadata, variables, ref_levels, random_effects = NULL,
                       method = c("LM_CLR", "CPLM"), output_dir = "maaslin_output") {
  method <- match.arg(method)

  params <- switch(method,
                   LM_CLR = list(norm = "CLR", trans = "NONE", ana = "LM"), #model for species
                   CPLM   = list(norm = "CLR", trans = "LOG",  ana = "CPLM") #model for ARGs and MGEs
  )

  Maaslin2(
    input_data = count_data,
    input_metadata  = metadata,
    output = output_dir,
    fixed_effects = variables,
    random_effects = random_effects,
    normalization = params$norm,transform = params$trans,
    analysis_method = params$ana,
    reference = paste(names(ref_levels), ref_levels, sep = ","),
    min_prevalence = 0, max_significance = 1,
    plot_heatmap = FALSE, plot_scatter = FALSE
  )
# Extract and format ouput table
  res_file <- file.path(output_dir, "all_results.tsv")
  read.delim(res_file) |>
    dplyr::filter(metadata %in% variables) |>
    dplyr::transmute(
      feature,
      variable  = metadata,
      level     = trimws(value),
      estimate  = coef, std.error = stderr, p.value = pval, q.value = qval,
      method    = method
    )
}
# Filter features
custom_filter <- function(df, prev_cutoff = NULL, abund_cutoff = NULL) {
  prevalence <- colSums(df > 0) / nrow(df)
  abundance  <- colMeans(df, na.rm = TRUE)
  keep <- prevalence >= prev_cutoff & abundance >= abund_cutoff
  df_filtered <- df[, keep, drop = FALSE]
  return(df_filtered)
}
#by prevalence 
prev_cutoff_sp   <- 0.4
